fields.name: M30
fields.description: Messier 30 is a globular cluster located in the southern constellation Capricornus. The cluster lies at around 27,140 light years from Earth.

fields.name: NGC6907
fields.description: NGC6907 is a barred spiral galaxy 137 million light years away with clearly defined, spread out spiral arms and a bar through the central of the galaxy.

fields.name: NGC6903
fields.description: NGC6903 is a lenticular galaxy - it is similar to a spiral galaxy in that it has has a disk shape but it has no spiral arms.

fields.name: IC1313
fields.description: IC1313 is a Galaxy in the Capricornus Constellation. IC1313 is approximatly 144 million ly.

fields.name: IC1321
fields.description: This is a barred spiral galaxy in the constellation of Capricornus. This spiral galaxy is around 289 million light years away.

fields.name: NGC457
fields.description: NGC457 is the brightest star cluster in the Cassiopeia constellation, 2,145 light years away. It is composed of around 80 stars, and is often called the 'Owl' or 'ET' cluster owing to its shape.

fields.name: NGC581
fields.description: NGC581 (also known as M103) is one of the more remote open clusters in the Messier catalogue. There are around 150 stars in this cluster.

fields.name: NGC7654
fields.description: NGC7654, also known as M52,  is a fine open cluster with 200 members. It has two yellow giant stars which are brighter than the others and lies 5,000 light years from Earth.

fields.name: NGC7789
fields.description: NGC 7789 is an open cluster in the constellation Cassiopeia, that was discovered by Caroline Herschel in 1783. Her brother William Herschel included it in his catalogue as H VI.30. This cluster is also known as "The White Rose" Cluster or "Caroline's Rose" Cluster because when seen visually, the loops of stars and dark lanes look like the swirling pattern of rose petals as seen from above. It lies 7600 light years from Earth.

fields.name: NGC281
fields.description: NGC281 is also known as the 'Pac-man' nebula due to its shape. Lying 10,000 light years away, it is a busy workshop of star formation. Prominent features include a small open cluster of stars, a diffuse red-glowing emission nebula, large lanes of obscuring gas and dust, and dense knots of dust and gas in which stars may still be forming.

fields.name: IC1795
fields.description: Located just over 6,000 light-years away, IC1795 is a bright nebula that is located close to the Heart Nebula, IC1805.

fields.name: NGC7635
fields.description: NGC7635, also known as Bubble Nebula, is a nebula that shines because it is heated by energy from a star almost 20 times as massive as our Sun.  The nebula lies 11,300 light years away.

fields.name: IC1747
fields.description: IC1747 is a Planetary nebula in the Cassiopeia Constellation, and is about 6700 light years away from us.

fields.name: IC289
fields.description: Located in the constellation of Cassiopeia, this is a very faint Planetary Nebula. It is around 4200 light years away.

fields.name: Abell84
fields.description: This is a faint and relatively small  planetary nebula that is in the Cassopeia constallation

fields.name: CassiopeiaA
fields.description: This is the youngest known supernova remnant in the Milky Way Galaxy. This was a Type II supernova whose light reached Earth in about 1667, but was not widely seen at that time. This supernovae remnant is 10,000 light years away.

fields.name: Tycho'sSNR
fields.description: Tycho'sSNR is a supernova remnant observed by Tycho Brahe on November 11, 1572. Although it lies 10,000 light years away, the object was as bright as Venus for many months, now all that is left is this faint nebulosity.

fields.name: NGC278
fields.description: NGC278 is a small, face-on spiral galaxy which looks very similar to a planetary nebula. It's located 26 million light years away.

fields.name: NGC4852
fields.description: NGC4852 is a reflection nebula situated 2,100 light years away in the constellation of Centaurus. It is an active region of star formation.

fields.name: NGC5617
fields.description: NGC5617 is an open cluster 2,600 light years away.

fields.name: PK315-0.1
fields.description: PK315-0.1 is a fairly bright planetary nebula in the constellation of Centaurus, just 6.7 light years away.

fields.name: NGC5307
fields.description: NGC 5307 is a planetary nebula located 10,000 light years away in the constellation Centaurus. This planetary nebulae has a spiral structure.

fields.name: NGC3918
fields.description: NGC3918 is a blue planetary nebula lying 2,600 light years away. It appears fairly spherical, with gas pushing out of the poles due to a hot wind from the central star.

fields.name: NGC6819
fields.description: NGC 6819 is an open cluster located 7,200 light years away in the Cygnus constellation. NGC6819 is a relatively small open cluster containing about 150 stars. It is also known as the 'Foxhead' star cluster.

fields.name: NGC6866
fields.description: NGC 6866 is an open cluster 5,000 light years away in the constellation Cygnus. It was discovered by Caroline Herschel on 23 July 1783.

fields.name: NGC6910
fields.description: NGC 6910 is a young open cluster visible in the Swan constellation 4,000 light years away.

fields.name: NGC6913
fields.description: NGC6913 (also known as M29) is a young open cluster located 3,000 light years away in the constellation Cygnus. It contains about 50  stars. There is a lot of dust between ourselves and this cluster, dimming the light from the stars.

fields.name: NGC7000
fields.description: NGC7000, known as the North America nebula, is an emission nebula in the constellation Cygnus, 1,600 light years away, close to Deneb. The remarkable shape of the nebula resembles that of the continent of North America, complete with a prominent Gulf of Mexico.

fields.name: NGC6888
fields.description: NGC6888, also known as the Crescent Nebula, is an emission nebula in the constellation Cygnus, about 5000 light-years away from Earth. It was discovered by Friedrich Wilhelm Herschel in 1792. It is formed by the fast stellar wind from the Wolf-Rayet star WR 136 (HD 192163) colliding with and energizing the slower moving wind ejected by the star when it became a red giant around 250,000 to 400,000 years ago.

fields.name: IC5146
fields.description: The Cocoon Nebula is a star forming region. The nebula is lit by the bright young star at the centre. It is roughly 4000 light years away.

fields.name: CRL2688
fields.description: Like a baby chick pecking its way out of an egg, the star in the center of the Egg Nebula is casting away shells of gas and dust as it slowly transforms itself into a white dwarf star. The star itself is obscured behind the gas and dust of this protoplanetary nebula. This nebula is 3000 light years away.

fields.name: NGC6894
fields.description: NGC6894 is a planetary nebula 4,000 light years away in the Cygnus constellation. The nebula is slightly pink in colour - due most likely to reddening of its light by dust clouds between ourselves and the nebula.

fields.name: NGC7026
fields.description: NGC7026 is a bipolar planetary nebula is situated in the constellation of Cygnus 4,500 light years away. It is somewhat rectangular in shape, with a dark dust lane in the middle, making it looks similar to a cheeseburger - hence its nickname, the 'Cheeseburger nebula'.

fields.name: NGC7027
fields.description: NGC7027 is a very young planetary nebula. The central star has a temperature of approximately 200,000 K, and is around 5000 times brighter than the Sun. It is this energy which causes the gas surrounding the star (and ejected by the star over the last few thousand years) to glow.

fields.name: NGC7048
fields.description: NGC 7048 is a planetary nebula in the constellation of Cygnus. The bright star to the lower left of the nebula is a magnitude 10.5 star, designated TYC 3589-4652-1. The central star of NGC 7048 is though to be a white dwarf.

fields.name: Barnard168
fields.description: Barnard 168 is a dark cloud where star formation can take place. It is located in the Swan constellation and is about 500 light years away from the solar system. The slightly brighter mist is the cocoon mist and is directly connected to the dark cloud.

fields.name: UGC11421
fields.description: UGC11421 is a fairly small galaxy in the constellation of Cygnus. It is classified as a 'barred lenticular' galaxy. A lenticular galaxy is similar to a spiral galaxy in that it has a central bulge, but is has no spiral arms. This galaxy has a bar through its centre, hence its classification as a barred lenticular.

fields.name: UGC11459
fields.description: UGC11459 is a small spiral galaxy in the constellation of Cygnus, with a very small or non-existent bulge.

fields.name: UGC11460
fields.description: UGC11460 is a small galaxy in the constellation of Cygnus, it's a spiral galaxy with a very small or non-existent bulge.

fields.name: UGC11781
fields.description: UGC11781 is classified as a mixed lenticular galaxy. Similar to other lenticulars the existence of a bar through the bulge, is possible.

fields.name: NGC288
fields.description: NGC288 is a globular cluster located 30,000 light years away in the constellation of Sculptor. It was discovered in 1785 by William Herschel. It contains over 100,000 as much material as the Sun.

fields.name: NGC40
fields.description: NGC40 is a planetary nebula located 3,000 light years away in the constellation Cepheus. The central star of this planetary nebula is a 'Wolf-Rayet' star. This type of star is very hot (100,000K) and blowing off it's mass at very high speeds as it nears the end of its life.

fields.name: M76
fields.description: This nebula is nicknamed 'The Little Dumbbell Nebula', due to its irregular appearance, although it is also known as the Cork Nebula, Butterfly Nebula, and Barbell Nebula. The star at the centre of the nebula blew off its material when it was in the Red Giant phase of its life. It will most likely end its life as a cool white dwarf in tens of billions of years time. M76 is around 4000 light years away in the Perseus constellation.

fields.name: NGC4147
fields.description: NGC4147 is a globular cluster 60,000 light years away in the constellation of Coma Berenices has a mass about that of 70,000 Suns.

fields.name: M53
fields.description: Messier 53 is a globular cluster in the Coma Berenices constellation. It has a mass of about 750,000 Suns and is around 4000 light years away.

fields.name: NGC5466
fields.description: NGC5466 is a globular cluster 55,000 light years away in the constellation of Bootes. It contains 3 binary star systems, an extremely rare occurrence in globular clusters where 2 stars orbit around each other.

fields.name: NGC5634
fields.description: NGC5634 is the only globular cluster in the constellation of Virgo, 88, 000 light years away. It was discovered in 1785 by William Herschel.

fields.name: M61
fields.description: This face-on spiral galaxy in the Virgo cluster has been the site for 3 supernovae observed in 1926,1961 and 1964. It is roughly 55 million light years away.

fields.name: M84
fields.description: This is an elliptical galaxy at the heart of the Virgo cluster. It lies at one end of a chain of galaxies in the cluster, known as the 'Markarian Chain'. This particular galaxy is roughly 60 million light years away.

fields.name: NGC4361
fields.description: NGC4361 is a planetary nebula 4,000 light years away in the constellation Corvus. It is only one of seven known planetary nebula with a so-called "quadrapolar structure" - that is, it has two pairs of bipolar lobes. These lobes were produced when the central star ejected its mass in two separate bursts.

fields.name: IC972
fields.description: This small, round Planetary Nebula is one of only 3 in the constellation of Virgo. It is also around 6400 light years away from us.

fields.name: NGC6229
fields.description: NGC6229 is a globular cluster located 99,000 light years away. It was discovered by William Herschel in 1787 and wrongly classified as planetary nebula. Its correct identification was made in the mid 19th century.

fields.name: NGC6440
fields.description: NGC6440 is a centrally concentrated globular cluster was discovered in 1784 by William Herschel.

fields.name: NGC6027
fields.description: NGC 6027 can be seen with other galaxies, all of which are part of a group of galaxies, known as Seyfert's Sextet. The group is interesting to astronomers since five of the galaxies have very similar velocities, implying they are all at around the same distance from Earth, except the small spiral galaxy which a velocity nearly four times larger than the others!

fields.name: NGC6070
fields.description: NGC6070 is a spiral galaxy 88 million light years away. It was one of the first objects looked at by the Sloan Digital Sky Survey in 1998. The Sloan survey is one of the largest astronomical sky surveys ever undertaken, and aims to map the positions and brightness of 100 million astronomical objects.

fields.name: NGC6210
fields.description: NGC6210 is a planetary nebula situated in the constellation Hercules. It appears very complex in structure due to jets of hot gas pushing through the cooler, outer shells of material.

fields.name: NGC6543
fields.description: NGC6543 is a planetary nebula found in the constellation of Draco 3,000 light years away. It has been nicknamed the 'Cat's Eye Nebula'. Its central star is a Wolf-Rayet star, which is very hot (100,000K) and ejecting its mass at very high speeds as it approaches the end of its life.

fields.name: NGC6535
fields.description: NGC6535 is a globular cluster situated 43,000 light years away in Serpens.

fields.name: M28
fields.description: Messier 28 is a globular cluster in the constellation Sagittarius. It was discovered by French astronomer Charles Messier on July 27, 1764 and is around 18,300 light years away.

fields.name: M22
fields.description: This globular cluster, discovered in 1665 is one of the nearest globular clusters to us and has a mass of about 1 million Suns. It is roughly 10,400 light years away from us.

fields.name: M16
fields.description: Located in Serpens Cauda, this nebula, also known as the 'Eagle nebula', has an open cluster embedded in it, formed from this massive gaseous dusty cloud. This nebula is around 6000 light years away.

fields.name: NGC6590
fields.description: NGC6590 is a small reflection nebula in the constellation of Sagittarius, lit by the stars embedded in it.

fields.name: NGC6818
fields.description: NGC6818 is a small bright planetary nebula 6,000 light years away, sometimes know as the Little Gem.

fields.name: NGC6826
fields.description: NGC6826 is a planetary nebula lying 3,000 light years away in the constellation of Cygnus. It is nicknamed the 'Blinking Nebula'. The central star is at a temperature of 45,000K and is 0.6 times more massive than our Sun. It is also one of the brightest central stars in all the planetary nebula which are visible.

fields.name: NGC6765
fields.description: NGC6765 is a planetary nebula in the constellation of Lyra.

fields.name: NGC7006
fields.description: NGC 7006 (also known as Caldwell 42) is a globular cluster in the constellation Delphinus. NGC 7006 resides in the outskirts of the Milky Way. It is about 135,000 light-years away, five times the distance between the Sun and the centre of the galaxy, and it is part of the galactic halo.

fields.name: NGC7492
fields.description: NGC7492 is a very loosely concentrated globular cluster,  one of the furthest GCs from us at a distance of 84,100 light years. NGC7492 is in the constellation Aquarius.

fields.name: NGC7129
fields.description: NGC 7129 is a reflection nebula located 3,300 light years away in the constellation Cepheus. A young open cluster is responsible for illuminating the surrounding nebula. A recent survey indicates the cluster contains more than 130 stars less than 1 million years old.

fields.name: NGC7662
fields.description: NGC7662 is a planetary nebula 4,000 light years away in the constellation of Andromeda. It is nicknamed the 'Blue Snowball'. It has a double ring structure - the inner ring visible due to a shock wave travelling through it, and the outer ring due to ionization from the hot central star.

fields.name: Pal1
fields.description: Pal1 is a globular cluster that is younger than other typical globular clusters, and appears quite loose, similar to an open cluster. It is thought that this globular cluster formed differently to the older clusters. While most globular clusters are thought to have formed at the same time as the Milky Way, the younger ones either formed more recently from leftover gas clouds, were captured by our Galaxy's gravity or may even be dwarf galaxies which have been cannibalised by the Milky Way.

fields.name: Pal2
fields.description: Pal2 is a globular cluster that appears redder than it actually is due to dust in the area between ourselves and the cluster. It lies 90,000 light years away.

fields.name: M79
fields.description: This globular cluster is thought to have originated from the nearby Canis Major dwarf galaxy which has recently interacted with our Milky Way galaxy. The cluster is around 42,000 light years away.

fields.name: NGC1232
fields.description: This is a beautiful face-on spiral in the Eridanus cluster, located about 70 million light years away. Regions where stars are forming in the spiral arms can clearly be seen as blue `knots' along the arms.

fields.name: NGC1300
fields.description: This is an excellent example of a barred spiral galaxy. The central bar is clear to see coming out from the central bulge, with the spiral arms located at the end of the bar.

fields.name: NGC1491
fields.description: NGC1491 is an emission nebula located 12,000 light years away in the constellation of Perseus. The nebula can be seeing glows red. Strong, energetic winds from this star are blowing the surrounding gas away from the star, giving it a bubble like appearance.

fields.name: M78
fields.description: This nebula in Orion is an active star forming region, illuminated by the bright stars inside the nebula. This nebula is part of a larger molecular cloud and is around 1500 light years from us.

fields.name: NGC1501
fields.description: NGC1501 is an elliptical-shaped planetary nebula located 5,000 light years away in the constellation of Camelopardalis. The nebula has a very hot (100,000K) so-called Wolf-Rayet star at its centre ejecting its mass at very high speeds as it approaches the end of its life.

fields.name: NGC1514
fields.description: NGC1535 is a spherical-looking planetary nebula located around 4,000 light years away. It was discovered in 1790 by William Herschel.

fields.name: NGC2022
fields.description: NGC2022 is a small, dim planetary nebula located 6,000 light years away in the constellation of Orion.

fields.name: M1
fields.description: The Crab Nebula is a supernova remnant in the constellation of Taurus. The nebula lies in the Perseus Arm of the Milky Way galaxy, at about 6,500 light years from Earth.

fields.name: NGC2419
fields.description: NGC2419 is a globular cluster nicknamed 'The Intergalactic Wanderer', as it was originally thought to be an intergalactic cluster.  We now know that it is gravitationally bound to our Galaxy and is one of the most luminous GCs in our Galaxy.

fields.name: NGC2261
fields.description: NGC2261 is a reflection nebula lit up by a variable star at the lower part of the nebula. It's located about 2,500 light years away.

fields.name: NGC2359
fields.description: NGC2359 is an emission nebula nicknamed 'Thor's Helmet' or the 'Duck Nebula'. It is located 16,000 light years away and lit up by a bright so-called Woif-Rayet star.

fields.name: NGC2392
fields.description: NGC2392 is a stunning planetary nebula located 5,000 light years away. Due to its shape, it has been nicknamed 'The Clown Face Nebula' or 'The Eskimo Nebula'.

fields.name: NGC2438
fields.description: NGC2438 is a ring-shaped planetary nebula located 2,900 light years away. It was discovered by William Herschel in 1786.

fields.name: NGC2440
fields.description: NGC2440 is a planetary nebula located 3,600 light years away. It is an interesting nebula with a lot of structure on its outskirts.

fields.name: Pal4
fields.description: Pal4 is the second most remote globular cluster 2nd most remote in the Milky Way, 356,000 light years from Earth.

fields.name: M95
fields.description: M95 is a barred-spiral galaxy located 38 million light years away in the constellation Leo. The spiral arms appear circular around the galaxy, making it look like a ring. It has a mass of about 50 billion suns stretches across 60,000 light years.

fields.name: M105
fields.description: Messier 105 is an elliptical galaxy in the constellation Leo. It was discovered in 1781 by Pierre Mechain, and was added to Messier's list in 1947.

fields.name: M109
fields.description: Discovered by Pierre Méchain in 1781, M109 is a 'barred' spiral galaxy which looks similar in shape to the Greek letter, 'Theta'. It is around 55 million light years away

fields.name: NGC3242
fields.description: NGC3242 is a planetary nebula known as the 'Ghost of Jupiter'. It's located 2,500 light years away in the constellation Hydra. The central white dwarf star has a mass about half that of our sun, and a temperature of 60,000K.

fields.name: M97
fields.description: M97 is a planetary nebula located 2,030 light years away in the constellation Ursa Major. it is one of the more complex planetary nebulae in structure, rather than being a simple sphere of gas. When a man named William Parsons observed the nebula, his illustration of it looked like an owl's head. It has been known as the Owl Nebula ever since.

fields.name: NGC2818A
fields.description: NGC2818A is a planetary nebula situated in an open cluster consisting of massive stars, most of which have ended their lives as supernovae and disappeared. In this cluster, one of the stars has shed its material resulting in the planetary nebula.

fields.name: NGC4365
fields.description: NGC4365 is an elliptical galaxy, assumed to lie just behind the main cluster itself. It is one of a third of elliptical galaxies which have a 'decouple core' - this means that the core of this galaxy rotates around a different axis than the rest of the galaxy. This sort of core occurs due to mergers with other galaxies which results in a lot of material being excreted.

fields.name: NGC4387
fields.description: NGC4387 is a dwarf elliptical galaxy in the Virgo cluster. This small, faint galaxy has a bright central core, and a faint extended halo.

fields.name: NGC4388
fields.description: NGC4388 is a nearly edge-on barred spiral galaxy in the Virgo galaxy cluster. It is classed as an active galaxy - it has a bright, energetic nucleus whose emission results from material being accreted onto the galaxy's central black hole.

fields.name: NGC4411b
fields.description: NGC4411b is a face-on barred spiral galaxy in the Virgo galaxy cluster, and was the site of a supernova explosion in 1992.

fields.name: IC3453
fields.description: IC 3453 is an irregular galaxy that is about 118 million light years from Earth and is located in the constellation of Berenice's hair. IC3453 has a comet like appearance.

fields.name: VCC530
fields.description: VCC530 is a very blue dwarf irregular galaxy in the Virgo cluster.

fields.name: IC3258
fields.description: This Irregular galaxy in the Virgo cluster has an extremely large blue shift - it is travelling towards us at 517km/s!
fields.avm_desc: Irregular Galaxy in Cluster of Galaxies

fields.name: NGC4438
fields.description: NGC4438 is an interacting galaxy and the most disrupted one in the Virgo galaxy cluster. It is thought to have interacted with NGC 4435 hundreds of millions of years ago, during which time stars and gas were pulled out of each galaxy. The matter torn out in the collision is now falling back onto NGC 4438.

fields.name: NGC4435
fields.description: NGC4435 is a lenticular galaxy next to NGC4438 in the Virgo galaxy cluster 55 million light years away. The pair of galaxies are sometimes called 'The Eyes' of Virgo.

fields.name: NGC4568
fields.description: NGC4568 is a spiral galaxy lying 55 million light years away. Together with NGC 4567, it is part of the system known as the 'Siamese Twins'. They may not be joined together however - this may just be how they appear on the sky.

fields.name: NGC4567
fields.description: NGC4567 is a spiral galaxy and part of the 'Siamese Twins', together with NGC 4568.

fields.name: NGC6054
fields.description: NGC6054 is a barred spiral galaxy in the Hercules galaxy cluster, it is interacting with another galaxy.

fields.name: NGC6045
fields.description: NGC6045 is an edge-on barred spiral galaxy in the Hercules galaxy cluster.

fields.name: NGC6047
fields.description: NGC6047 is an elliptical galaxy in the Hercules constellation.

fields.name: NGC6041
fields.description: NGC 6041 is a bright lenticular galaxy, meaning it is between an elliptical and a spiral. It is located in the constellation Hercules and about 400,000 light years  from Earth.

fields.name: NGC4615
fields.description: NGC4615 is a beautiful spiral galaxy in the Coma galaxy cluster.

fields.name: NGC5025
fields.description: NGC5025 is an edge-on barred spiral galaxy in the Coma galaxy cluster.

fields.name: NGC5065
fields.description: NGC5065 is a spiral galaxy in the Coma galaxy cluster.

fields.name: NGC5089
fields.description: NGC5089 is a barred spiral galaxy in the Coma galaxy cluster.

fields.name: NGC4627
fields.description: NGC4627 is an elliptical galaxy in the Coma galaxy cluster. It has been distorted by the larger spiral galaxy (NGC 4631).

fields.name: NGC4673
fields.description: NGC4673 is an Elliptical galaxy in the Coma galaxy cluster.

fields.name: NGC4881
fields.description: NGC4881 is an Elliptical galaxy in the Coma galaxy cluster.

fields.name: UGC8363
fields.description: UGC8363 is an irregular galaxy in the Coma galaxy cluster.

fields.name: UGC6930
fields.description: UGC6930 is classified as a barred spiral galaxy.

fields.name: NGC3953
fields.description: NGC3953 is a barred spiral galaxy. It has a mass of about 140 billion Suns, small, bright core and large, knotty spiral arms. These knots are regions of ionised Hydrogen (HII).

fields.name: NGC3718
fields.description: NGC3718 is a barred spiral galaxy in Ursa Major constellation. It has a bright yellow central core, with a very diffuse surrounding envelope. The spiral arm structure of this galaxy is not clear for this galaxy.

fields.name: NGC3726
fields.description: NGC3726 is a barred spiral galaxy in the Ursa Major cluster of galaxies, it has the mass one a couple of hundred billion Suns.

fields.name: NGC3769
fields.description: NGC3769 is a barred spiral  galaxy in the constellation Ursa Major.

fields.name: NGC4157
fields.description: NGC4157 is a nearly edge-on barred spiral galaxy in the Ursa Major cluster of galaxies.

fields.name: NGC2693
fields.description: NGC2693 is an 'elliptical' galaxy, a type without spiral arms, lying 186 million light years away.

fields.name: NGC3690
fields.description: NGC3690 is a galaxy made up of two galaxies that have collided. This interaction has caused a burst of star formation and the galaxies contain many bright young stars.

fields.name: NGC3309
fields.description: NGC3309 is an elliptical galaxy. It is one of a pair of galaxies at the centre of the Hydra galaxy cluster, the second being NGC 3311.

fields.name: NGC3311
fields.description: NGC3311 is an elliptical galaxy. It is one of a pair of galaxies (together with NGC 3309) at the centre of the Hydra galaxy cluster. NGC 3311 is a super-giant elliptical - one of the largest and most luminous galaxies in the Universe.

fields.name: IC2597
fields.description: IC 2597 is a faint elliptical galaxy that is about 104 million light years from Earth and is found in the constellation of the Water Snake .

fields.name: NGC3336
fields.description: NGC3336 is a faint spiral galaxy in the Hydra cluster.

fields.name: NGC3312
fields.description: NGC3312 is a faint nearly edge-on spiral galaxy in the Hydra galaxy cluster.

fields.name: NGC3285
fields.description: NGC3285 is a spiral galaxy in the Hydra galaxy cluster.

fields.name: NGC3285B
fields.description: NGC3285B is a small spiral galaxy in the Hydra galaxy cluster.

fields.name: M101
fields.description: This spiral galaxy in the constellation of Ursa Major is more commonly known as the 'Pinwheel Galaxy'. It was discovered in 1781, and was one of the last entries in the Messier Catalogue. M101 has been the location of 3 supernovae events - in 1909, 1951 and 1970. It is around 25 million light years away.

fields.name: NGC5474
fields.description: NGC5474 is a nearly face-on spiral galaxy 20 million light years away. It is very interesting to observe as, ulike most galaxy cores, this one appears somewhat offset from the centre of the galaxy, due to the gravitational interaction that this galaxy is undergoing with its large neighbour, M101.

fields.name: NGC5585
fields.description: NGC5585 is a spiral galaxy and of the furthest lying members of the M101 group of galaxies.

fields.name: NGC5204
fields.description: NGC5204 has been classified by astronomers as a spiral and irregular galaxy, due to the appearance of its spiral arms, which are not very well defined. It has quite a bright centre.

fields.name: UGC8508
fields.description: UGC8508 is a dwarf irregular galaxy in the M101 group of galaxies.

fields.name: UGC8837
fields.description: UGC8837 , also known as Holmberg IV, is a dwarf irregular galaxy in the M101 galaxy group.

fields.name: M96
fields.description: M96 is a spiral galaxy located 35 million light years away in the constellation Leo. It is the brightest member of the M96 galaxy group. The galaxy has a mass of about 80 billion Suns.

fields.name: NGC3299
fields.description: NGC3299 is a small spiral galaxy in the M96 group of galaxies.

fields.name: NGC3377
fields.description: NGC3377 is an elliptical galaxy in the M96 group of galaxies. At its centre is believed to lie a super-massive black hole with a mass of about 200 million suns!

fields.name: NGC3384
fields.description: NGC3384 is a barred lenticular galaxy in the M96 galaxy group. It is thought to have collided with M96 500 million years ago.

fields.name: NGC1023
fields.description: NGC1023 is a barred lenticular galaxy - it has a disk and central bulge like our Galaxy, but no spiral arms. The galaxies lies between between 30 and 64 million light years away. By studying the velocities of the stars at its centre, astronomers have deduced that there must be a supermassive black hole the centre of this galaxy.

fields.name: NGC925
fields.description: NGC 925 is a barred spiral galaxy located about 30 million light-years away in the constellation Triangulum.

fields.name: NGC949
fields.description: NGC949 is a small spiral galaxy in the NGC1023 galaxy group. The galaxy has an unusual shape, made more obscure due to its inclination.

fields.name: NGC959
fields.description: NGC959 is a galaxy in the Triangulum Constellation. The galaxy was discovered in 1876 by astronomer Édouard Stephan.

fields.name: NGC1003
fields.description: NGC1003 is a spiral galaxy located in the Perseus constellation about 28 million light years from the Milky Way. It was discovered by the German-British astronomer William Herschel in 1784.

fields.name: NGC1325
fields.description: NGC 1325 is a barred spiral galaxy of Hubble type SA (s) bc in the constellation Eridanus at the southern sky. The galaxy was discovered by the astronomer William Herschel on 19 December 1798.

fields.name: NGC1385
fields.description: NGC1385 is a spiral galaxy with an irregular appearance located in the Eridanus galaxy cluster.

fields.name: NGC1332
fields.description: NGC1332 is a lenticular galaxy in the Eridanus galaxy cluster around 75 million light years away.

fields.name: NGC1395
fields.description: NGC1395 is a seyfert galaxy meaning the centre of the galaxy (called the nucleus) is small and intensely bright.

fields.name: NGC1407
fields.description: NGC1407 is an elliptical galaxy lying about 70 million light years away in the Eridanus galaxy cluster.

fields.name: NGC1426
fields.description: NGC1426 is a rather small elliptical galaxy in the Eridanus galaxy cluster.

fields.name: NGC2339
fields.description: NGC2339 is a face-on spiral galaxy with a central bar, and well defined spiral arms. It is located 97 million light years away.

fields.name: NGC2158
fields.description: NGC2158 is a well-populated open cluster with about 1000 star members, making it look similar to a globular cluster. The cluster is located 16,000 light years.

fields.name: NGC2266
fields.description: NGC2266 is an open cluster containing about 190 stars, many of which are red giants who are in the phase of their evolution where they are burning a shell of Hydrogen around their core. The blue stars in the cluster are still burning the Hydrogen in their core. The galaxy is located about 11,000 light years away.

fields.name: NGC2129
fields.description: NGC2129 has been classified as a young open cluster located 5,000 light years away, however recent studies have found that a number of stars in this cluster are actually at a variety of distances.

fields.name: UGCA91
fields.description: UGCA91 is a globular cluster lying 294,000 light years away, making it one of the most distant globular clusters around the Milky Way.

fields.name: Pal3
fields.description: Pal3 is a globular cluster, discovered in 1955 and initially thought to be a dwarf galaxy, although it has now been reclassified as a diffuse globular cluster. It is located 302,000 light years from Earth.

fields.name: NGC5897
fields.description: NGC5897 is a globular cluster with a mass of 200,000 suns. It contains about 40 so-called 'blue stragglers' - these are stars which are bright and blue, and therefore appear younger than the globular cluster's age. A possible reason for this is that they may have lost their outer layers during collisions with other stars.

fields.name: NGC6093
fields.description: NGC6093 is a globular cluster 30,000 light years away, also known as M80 contains a large number of 'blue stragglers' - stars which are bright and blue, and therefore appear younger than the globular cluster's age. A possible reason for this is that they may have lost their outer layers during collisions with other stars.

fields.name: NGC6341
fields.description: NGC6341 is a globular cluster located 26,700 light years away. This cluster contains a few variable stars, and also an eclipsing binary star system (two stars orbiting each other along our line of sight), which are rare in such objects.

fields.name: NGC6366
fields.description: NGC6366 is a very diffuse globular cluster, which looks similar to an open cluster. Unlike many other globular clusters, it is rather rich in elements heavier than Helium, thus it is said to be 'metal-rich'.

fields.name: NGC6712
fields.description: NGC6712 is a globular cluster located 25,000 light years from Earth. The cluster passed through the plane of the Milky Way a few million years ago - the result of such interactions is that many of the lighter stars in this cluster have been stripped away, leaving only about 1% of its original mass. It is one of around 12 globular cluster in the galaxy which is a bright source of X-rays.

fields.name: NGC6749
fields.description: NGC6749 is a globular cluster 25,800 light years away in the constellation Aquila. It is is very diffuse and appears similar to an open cluster.

fields.name: NGC6838
fields.description: NGC6838 is a loose globular cluster, although for a long period of time many astronomers considered it to be a dense open cluster. It lies 13,000 light years from Earth.

fields.name: NGC6934
fields.description: NGC6934 is a globular cluster in the constellation of Delphinus, 50,000 light years away in the halo of our Galaxy. It has a mass of about 200,000 Suns, and is though to be a remnant of a tidally disrupted dwarf galaxy which was orbiting the Milky Way.

fields.name: HCG1
fields.description: HCG1 is a Galaxy Cluster in the Andromeda Constellation. This group of galaxies has two interacting galaxies and another two young galaxies.

fields.name: HCG8
fields.description: HCG8 is a Galaxy cluster in the Andromeda Constellation. This quartet contains a bright eliptical galaxy and three compact galaxies. The elliptical galaxy is unusual as its central region appears to be peanut shaped.

fields.name: HCG9
fields.description: HCG9 is a Galaxy cluster in the Cetus Constellation. This group consists of four galaxies.

fields.name: HCG35
fields.description: HCG35 is a Galaxy cluster in the Lynx Constellation. This is a galaxy group made up of six galaxies.

fields.name: HCG99
fields.description: HCG99 is a Galaxy cluster in the Pegasus constellation. This group is a set of five galaxies including a pair of galaxies that are interacting with each other.

fields.name: HCG100
fields.description: HCG100 is a Galaxy Cluster in the Pegasus Constellation. This group of galaxies is a set of four spiral galaxies.

fields.name: HCG12
fields.description: HCG12 is a Galaxy Cluster in the Cetus Constellation. This group is made up of a set of five galaxies.

fields.name: HCG13
fields.description: HCG13 is a Galaxy Cluster in the Cetus Constellation. This group comprises of a bright spiral galaxy and an eliptical galaxy plus three smaller galaxies.

fields.name: HCG4
fields.description: HCG4 is a Galaxy cluster in the Cetus Constellation.

fields.name: HCG17
fields.description: HCG17 is a Galaxy Cluster in the Aries Constellation. This group of galaxies is a set of five galaxies all packed closely together.

fields.name: HCG18
fields.description: HCG18 is an irregular galaxy in the Aries constellation. It was thought to be a group of galaxies at first but in 1999 the object was found to be a single galaxy with several places where stars are forming.

fields.name: HCG19
fields.description: HCG19 is a Galaxy cluster in the Cetus Constellation. This group consists of an elliptical galaxy plus three smaller spiral galaxies.

fields.name: HCG20
fields.description: This is a group of six galaxies in the Aries Constellation.

fields.name: HCG26
fields.description: HCG26 is a Galaxy cluster in the Eridanus constellation. This is a very packed together group of seven galaxies. The large spiral galaxy in the group looks like its in contact with three other galaxies.

fields.name: HCG27
fields.description: HCG27 is a Galaxy cluster in the Eridanus constellation. This group of galaxies is made up of four galaxies that are moving away from us quickly and two that are moving away from us slowly.

fields.name: HCG28
fields.description: HCG28 is a Galaxy cluster in the Eridanus constellation. This set of four galaxies consists of a set of 3 galaxies packed closely together and a smaller galaxy.

fields.name: HCG29
fields.description: HCG29 is a Galaxy cluster in the Eridanus Constellation. This group of galaxies is a set of four galaxies all in a straight line. The brightest galaxy is compact and very blue.

fields.name: HCG31
fields.description: HCG31 is a Galaxy cluster in the Eridanus Constellation. It looks like one of the galaxies in this group is creating alot of new stars at the moment. We think this is because of other galaxies in the surrounding area interacting with it.

fields.name: HCG32
fields.description: HCG32 is a Galaxy cluster in the Lepus constellation. This is a distant set of four galaxies.

fields.name: HCG33
fields.description: HCG33 is a Galaxy cluster in the Taurus Constellation. This is a set of four mainly eliptical galaxies all packed together.

fields.name: HCG34
fields.description: HCG34 is a Galaxy cluster in the Orion Constellation. This group contains a large, bright elliptical galaxy surrounded by three smaller, fainter galaxies.

fields.name: HCG36
fields.description: HCG36 is a Galaxy cluster in the Cancer Constellation. This group contains four galaxies.

fields.name: HCG38
fields.description: HCG38 is a Galaxy cluster in the Leo constellation. This group contains an interacting pair of galaxies, and two other galaxies.

fields.name: HCG39
fields.description: HCG39 is a Galaxy cluster in the Hydra Constellation. This group is made up of four galaxies all in a line. Interestingly, the galaxies are all evenly spaced between each other too!

fields.name: HCG40
fields.description: HCG40 is a Galaxy cluster in the Hydra Constellation. This group is a very closely packed set of five overlapping galaxies.  There are three spiral galaxies in the group.

fields.name: HCG46
fields.description: HCG46 is a Galaxy cluster in the Leo Constellation. This group is a set of four galaxies. Two of the galaxies look like they're interacting.

fields.name: HCG47
fields.description: HCG47 is a Galaxy cluster in the Leo Constellation. This set of four galaxies contains a peculiar elliptical Galaxy which looks like its attached by a bright bridge to the bright spiral galaxy.

fields.name: HCG52
fields.description: HCG52 is a Galaxy cluster in the Leo Constellation. This is a loose set of three spiral galaxies plus a fainter spiral galaxy.

fields.name: HCG54
fields.description: HCG54 is a Galaxy cluster in the Leo Constellation. This group is made up of a set of four galaxies that are all in an organised line.

fields.name: HCG59
fields.description: HCG59 is a Galaxy cluster in the Leo Constellation. This group is made up of four small galaxies and a very fast moving faint galaxy.

fields.name: HCG63
fields.description: HCG63 is a Galaxy cluster in the Centaurus Constellation. This galaxy group is a set of three galaxies and a very slow moving fainter galaxy.

fields.name: HCG64
fields.description: HCG64 is a Galaxy cluster in the Virgo Constellation. This small group is made up of a set of three mostly spiral galaxies that are all interacting. Large plumes of bright material can be seen extending from the galaxies.

fields.name: HCG65
fields.description: HCG65 is a Galaxy cluster in the Hydra Constellation. This is a closely packed set of five galaxies.

fields.name: HCG69
fields.description: HCG69 is a Galaxy cluster in the Boötes constellation. This is a compact quartet of mostly spiral galaxies.

fields.name: HCG72
fields.description: HCG72 is a Galaxy cluster in the Boötes constellation. This group contains four galaxies that are all moving at similar speeds away from us.

fields.name: HCG74
fields.description: HCG74 is a Galaxy Cluster in the Serpens Constellation. This group is a set of five galaxies containing a larger elliptical galaxy with two very close smaller galaxies.

fields.name: HCG75
fields.description: HCG75 is a Galaxy cluster in the Serpens Constellation. This group is a set of six galaxies containing three galaxies that overlap in images.

fields.name: HCG77
fields.description: HCG77 is a Galaxy cluster in the Serpens Constellation. This group consists of a pair of galaxies that are moving away from us quickly and interact with each other. The centre of one of these galaxies is likely too be a massive black hole.

fields.name: HCG79
fields.description: HCG79 is a Galaxy cluster in the Serpens Constellation. This is a very tightly packed group of galaxies, it is so small that it would fit entirely within the Milky Way galaxy!

fields.name: HCG81
fields.description: HCG81 is a Galaxy cluster in the Hercules Constellation. This is a compact group of four galaxies.

fields.name: HCG87
fields.description: HCG 87 is a compact group of galaxies listed in the Hickson Compact Group Catalogue. This group is about 400 million light-years away in the constellation Capricornus.

fields.name: HCG94
fields.description: HCG94 is a Galaxy cluster in the Pegasus Constellation. This is a group of seven galaxies all travelling in roughly the same direction at the same speed.

fields.name: HCG95
fields.description: HCG95 is a Galaxy cluster in the Pegasus Constellation. This group of 4 galaxies includes a set of interacting galaxies.

fields.name: HCG96
fields.description: HCG96 is a Galaxy cluster in the Pegasus Constellation. This is a group of four galaxies containing a bright spiral galaxy.

fields.name: HCG98
fields.description: HCG98 is a Galaxy cluster in the Pisces Constellation. This group contains a close pair of galaxies with a nearby smaller companion galaxy.

fields.name: NGC2467
fields.description: NGC2467 is an open cluster s surround by a diffuse nebulosity. It is located 17,000 light years away in the constellation of Puppis.

fields.name: NGC346
fields.description: NGC346 is an open cluster found in the Small Magellanic Cloud, a small irregular galaxy orbiting our Milky Way Galaxy 210,000 light years away.

fields.name: NGC2626
fields.description: NGC2626 is a reflection nebula located 3,300 light years lit up largely by a central, blue star.

fields.name: NGC7833
fields.description: NGC7833 is an open cluster consisting of only 4 stars in the constellation of Pegasus.

fields.name: M103
fields.description: This open cluster is situated in the constellation of Cassiopeia. There are about 228 stars in the region of this cluster which have been studied by astronomers - only 77 of which have been found to be in the cluster. Of all the stars in the cluster, there is only 1 red giant star. M103 is around 9000 light years away from us.

fields.name: NGC637
fields.description: NGC637 is an open cluster is located in the constellation of Cassiopeia about 7,000 light years away.

fields.name: Czernik6
fields.description: Czernik6 is an Open Cluster in the Cassiopeia Constellation. This open cluster only has 6 stars.

fields.name: Czernik12
fields.description: Czernik12 is an open cluster located in the constellation of Perseus.

fields.name: NGC1193
fields.description: NGC1193 is an old open cluster is located in the constellation Perseus.

fields.name: NGC1348
fields.description: NGC1348 is an open cluster located around 6,194 light years in the Perseus Constellation. The cluster only contains about 20 stars.

fields.name: NGC5998
fields.description: NGC5998 open cluster is located in the constellation of Scorpius.

fields.name: IC3568
fields.description: IC 3568 is a planetary nebula that is 4500 ly away from Earth in the constellation of Camelopardalis. It is a relatively young nebula. It was dubbed the Lemon Slice Nebula by Jim Kaler, due to its appearance in one image from the Hubble Space Telescope.

fields.name: NGC6611
fields.description: NGC6611 is an open cluster, also known as M16, located 7,000 light years away. The cluster is embedded in a cloud of gas known as the Eagle nebula, from which it formed. It is in fact the light from the young, hot stars in this cluster which excites the gas cloud and causes it to shine.

fields.name: ESO518-03
fields.description: ESO518-03 is a globular cluster located in the constellation Ophiuchus. It is 30,300 light years away from earth.

fields.name: ESO587-04
fields.description: ESO518-03 is a is a globular cluster located in the constellation Ophiuchus. It is 30,300 light years away from earth.

fields.name: Ruprecht135
fields.description: Ruprecht135 is an open galactic cluster that is moving towards us at 0.71 km per second.

fields.name: NGC6756
fields.description: NGC6756 is an open cluster 11,000 light years away in the constellation of Aquila. It  contains about 40 member stars.

fields.name: NGC6802
fields.description: NGC6802 is an open cluster 4,000 light years away in the constellation of Vulpecula is relatively old and small.

fields.name: NGC6309
fields.description: NGC 6309, also known as the 'Box Nebula', is a planetary nebula located in the constellation Ophiuchus. It has a luminosity of about 1800 times of the Sun.

fields.name: NGC6720
fields.description: NGC6720 is a planetary nebula, also known as the 'Ring Nebula', located 2,000 light years from Earth. It is thought to have formed 1,000 years ago when an old star blew off its surrounding material. The inner part of the nebula which appears dark is actually emitting hot, UV radiation which is invisible to our eyes. The central white dwarf star is planet-sized, and was probably once a Sun-like star.

fields.name: NGC7036
fields.description: NGC7036's nature is unknown. The object was investigated by professional astronomers in 2002, as there was some uncertainty as to whether or not it actually is a star cluster or just a projection of stars at varying distances, on the sky. Its nature is still undetermined.

fields.name: NGC7128
fields.description: NGC7128 is an open cluster 13,000 light years away in the Cygnus Constellation. It was first discovered by William Herschel on October 14, 1787.

fields.name: NGC7296
fields.description: NGC7296 is an open cluster located in the constellation of Lacerta. This object is considered to be the same as NGC 7295.

fields.name: Czernik44
fields.description: Czernik44 is an open cluster in Cassiopeia Constellation

fields.name: NGC7788
fields.description: NGC7788 is a scattered cluster of about 25 stars in the constellation of Cassiopeia. NGC 7788 was first identified by John Herschel in 1829.

fields.name: NGC7008
fields.description: NGC 7008, also known as the Fetus Nebula, is a planetary nebula with a diameter of approximately 1 light-year located at a distance of 2800 light years in the Cygnus constellation.

fields.name: NGC2185
fields.description: NGC2185 is a reflection nebula and is thought to be midway between a cold dust or gas cloud, and an emission nebula. It is located 3,000 light years away.

fields.name: NGC1999
fields.description: NGC1999 is a emission and reflection nebula located 1,000 light years away in the constellation of Orion. This nebula is lit up by its central star, V380.

fields.name: Mayer2
fields.description: The Mayer2 is an open galactic cluster.

fields.name: NGC1605
fields.description: NGC1605 is an open cluster located 8,342 light years away in the Perseus constellation.

fields.name: NGC1624
fields.description: NGC1624 is an open star cluster made up of just a few stars embedded within a diffuse reddish nebula.

fields.name: NGC1798
fields.description: NGC1798 is an open cluster located in the constellation of Auriga. It has about 50 member stars and a number of faint background stars can be seen.

fields.name: NGC1883
fields.description: NGC1883 is an open cluster located 15,648 light years away in the constellation Auriga and is about a billion years old.

fields.name: Berkeley73
fields.description: Berkeley 73 is about 1.5 billion years old and is a faint open cluster.

fields.name: NGC2225
fields.description: NGC2225 is a small open cluster with about 40 member stars, located in the constellation of Monoceros.

fields.name: Czernik27
fields.description: Czernik27 is an open cluster located in the constellation of Monoceros.

fields.name: Ruprecht26
fields.description: Ruprecht26 is a open cluster that is located in the constellation of Puppis.

fields.name: NGC2242
fields.description: NGC2242 is a planetary nebula located in the constellation of Auriga. It was discovered in 1886 by Lewis Swift, but it was not until 1987 that it was found to be a planetary nebula - it was originally thought to be a galaxy.

fields.name: NGC3231
fields.description: NGC3231 is an open cluster in the constellation of Ursa Major.

fields.name: IC4662
fields.description: This small irregular galaxy is known as a 'dwarf' galaxy - a small galaxy containing only a million or so stars, and thought to be full of Dark Matter. IC4662 is roughly 13.1 million light years away.

fields.name: NGC6630
fields.description: NGC6630 is an interacting elliptical galaxy in the constellation of Pavo, 116 million light years away.

fields.name: NGC6684
fields.description: NGC6684 is a barred spiral galaxy 37 million light years away in the constellation Pavo.

fields.name: NGC6025
fields.description: NGC6025 open cluster that was discovered in 1751. The presence of very faint unresolved stars in this cluster gives the appearance of a faint nebula throughout the area.

fields.name: NGC5921
fields.description: NGC5921 is a small barred spiral galaxy is at the centre of Serpens Caput (the head of the snake depicting the constellation Serpens).

fields.name: PRCD-51
fields.description: PRCD-51 is an interesting galaxy lying 600 million light years ago. It looks extremely similar to a planetary nebula. The ring around the central galaxy contains mainly clusters of young, blue stars, contrasting with the nucleus containing old, yellow stars.

fields.name: NGC6539
fields.description: NGC6539 is a globular cluster, located 27,000 light years away in the constellation Serpens.

fields.name: NGC1555
fields.description: NGC1555 is a diffuse nebula lit up by a star within the Taurus constellation.

fields.name: IC349
fields.description: IC 349, also known as Barnard's Merope Nebula, is a nebula which lies 0.06 light years from the star Merope in the Pleiades cluster, Taurus Constellation.  As it is so near to the star, it is quite difficult to observe.

fields.name: NGC1587
fields.description: NGC1587 is an elliptical galaxy in the constellation of Taurus.

fields.name: NGC1589
fields.description: NGC1589 is an edge-on spiral galaxy with a bright centre and tightly wound spiral arms.

fields.name: NGC1642
fields.description: NGC1642 is a pretty face-on spiral galaxy.

fields.name: Abell28
fields.description: George Abell compiled his list of planetary nebulae in 1966 after searching through photographs. Abell 28 is the only one which he found in the Ursa Major constellation. This is a faint nebulae where the brightness is not the same around the disk.

fields.name: M87
fields.description: M87 is a giant elliptical galaxy location 50 million light years away, at the centre of the Virgo cluster of galaxies. It contains a huge number of globular clusters, more than 12,000 compared to our Galaxy's 150.

fields.name: M86
fields.description: M88 is an elliptical galaxy situated 55 million light years away, in the Virgo cluster. An interesting fact about this galaxy is that it is approaching us at a speed of 280 miles per second!

fields.name: M90
fields.description: M90 is a large, spiral galaxy located 55 million light years at the core of the Virgo cluster. It has tightly wound spiral arms, with no evidence of ongoing star formation in them. This galaxy is approaching our at the speed of 383 km per second.

fields.name: NGC1049
fields.description: NGC 1049 is a globular cluster located in the Fornax Dwarf galaxy. At a distance of 630,000 light years, it is visible in moderate sized telescopes, while the parent galaxy is nearly invisible.

fields.name: NGC7814
fields.description: NGC 7814 (also known as UGC 8 or Caldwell 43) is a spiral galaxy about 40 million light-years away in the constellation Pegasus. The galaxy is seen edge-on from Earth. It is sometimes referred to as "the little sombrero", a miniature version of Messier 104.

fields.name: NGC185
fields.description: NGC 185 (also known as Caldwell 18) is a dwarf spheroidal galaxy located 2 million light-years in the constellation Cassiopeia. It is a satellite of the Andromeda Galaxy.

fields.name: M32
fields.description: Messier 32, also known as Le Gentil, is a dwarf elliptical galaxy located in Andromeda constellation. The galaxy lies at a distance of 2.49 million light years from Earth. M32 is a satellite galaxy of M31, the famous Andromeda Galaxy.

fields.name: M33
fields.description: The Triangulum Galaxy is a spiral galaxy approximately 3 million light-years from Earth in the constellation Triangulum. It is catalogued as Messier 33 , and is sometimes informally referred to as the Pinwheel Galaxy, a nickname it shares with Messier 101. The Triangulum Galaxy is the third-largest member of the Local Group of galaxies, behind the Milky Way and the Andromeda Galaxy.

fields.name: M74
fields.description: Messier 74, nicknamed the Phantom Galaxy, is a grand design spiral galaxy located in the constellation Pisces. The galaxy looks like its facing the Earth face-on. It lies at an approximate distance of 30 million light years from Earth.

fields.name: NGC772
fields.description: NGC772 is an unbarred spiral galaxy approximately 130 million light-years away in the constellation Aries.

fields.name: NGC936
fields.description: NGC936 is a barred lenticular galaxy - it has a disc shape with a central bar, but no spiral arms.

fields.name: M77
fields.description: Messier 77, also known as Cetus A, is a barred spiral galaxy located in the constellation Cetus. It lies at a distance of 47 million light years.

fields.name: NGC7822
fields.description: NGC 7822 is a young star-forming complex in the constellation of Cepheus. The complex is believed to be some 2,900 light years distant, with the younger components aged no more than a few million years.

fields.name: IC59
fields.description: This is an emission nebula in the constellation of Cassiopeia.

fields.name: NGC246
fields.description: NGC246 is a planetary nebula. The central star has a temperature of over 130,000 K, compared to our Sun, which shines at just 6000 K.

fields.name: PNG144.3-15.5
fields.description: PNG144.3-15.5 is quite a small Planetary Nebula.

fields.name: M68
fields.description: Messier 68 is a globular cluster in the constellation Hydra. This globular cluster  is 33,000 light years away from Earth.

fields.name: M3
fields.description: Messier 3 is a globular cluster of stars in the northern constellation of Canes Venatici. This globular cluster is very densely packed and contains more than 500,000 stars.

fields.name: NGC5694
fields.description: NGC5694 is a small, densely packed globular cluster in the constellation of Hydra, 113,000 light years away.

fields.name: NGC4038
fields.description: The two galaxies named NGC 4038 and NGC 4039 are a pair of interacting galaxies known as the Antennae. These two galaxies were originally spiral in shape, but over time, their interaction has caused them to distort into the strange looking 'comma' shape. Such a merger has resulted in intense star formation, seen as the blue areas of this object.

fields.name: NGC4214
fields.description: NGC4214 is an irregular dwarf galaxy 15 million light years away.  The bright regions show where intense star formation is occurring in the galaxy.

fields.name: M85
fields.description: This is a lenticular galaxy, consisting mainly of old, yellow stars although there are some younger stars in the centre of the galaxy. A lenticular galaxy is a disk galaxy, similar to a spiral, but without the spiral arms. M85 is an example of a face-on lenticular.

fields.name: NGC4449
fields.description: NGC4449 is a barred irregular galaxy, located approximately 13 million light years away. Star formation is ongoing in this galaxy, as can be seen by the bright regions scattered throughout the galaxy.

fields.name: NGC4535
fields.description: NGC 4535 is a barred spiral galaxy located some 54 million light years from Earth in the constellation Virgo. It is a member of the Virgo Cluster of galaxies.

fields.name: M104
fields.description: The Sombrero Galaxy is an unbarred spiral galaxy in the constellation Virgo around 31 million light-years from Earth. This galaxy is about 30% of the size of the Milky Way.

fields.name: NGC4647
fields.description: NGC 4647 is the spiral galaxy companion of M60, an elliptical galaxy in the Virgo cluster of galaxies. The spiral galaxy's blue colour is a result of the intense star formation occurring along the arms of the galaxy. M60 contains old stars, and thus appears yellow.

fields.name: M64
fields.description: This spiral galaxy is nicknamed the `Black Eye Galaxy', due to the shape of the dark dust lane visible along the edge of the galaxy which blocks the light from stars behind. It is a spiral galaxy in the Coma Berenices constellation.

fields.name: M63
fields.description: This galaxy, known as the `Sunflower Galaxy', is an example of a `flocculent' spiral galaxy - unlike other spirals which have obvious spiral arms, this galaxy does not have clearly spaced arms. The bright blue regions indicate where stars are currently forming.

fields.name: M51
fields.description: This face-on spiral galaxy is more commonly known as the `Whirlpool galaxy' due to its distinctive spiral arms. Dark lanes where dust obscures the light from stars and blue patches where stars are currently forming can both clearly be seen in this beautiful galaxy.

fields.name: NGC6144
fields.description: NGC 6144 is a globular cluster in the constellation Scorpius 33,500 light years away. This globular cluster is moving away from us at about 102 km per second.

fields.name: M107
fields.description: 21,000 light years away, this globular cluster is approaching us at 147 km/s.

fields.name: M13
fields.description: Discovered by Edmond Halley in 1714, this cluster, nicknamed the `Hercules Cluster'  may contain more than a million stars!

fields.name: M10
fields.description: Messier 10 or M10 is a globular cluster of stars in the constellation of Ophiuchus and is around 14,400 light years away. The object was discovered by the French astronomer Charles Messier on May 29, 1764, who catalogued it as number 10 in his catalogue and described it as a "nebula without stars".  The hot, young blue stars and the older, yellow stars will be clear to see.

fields.name: M92
fields.description: Messier 92 is a globular cluster of stars in the northern constellation of Hercules. Globular clusters are some of the oldest structures in the Galaxy; this one is probably more than 14 billion years old.

fields.name: M9
fields.description: M9 is a globular cluster located 25,800 light years away in the constellation Ophiuchus. It is one of the closest clusters to the centre of our galaxy.

fields.name: M14
fields.description: The blue stars are young and hot, whereas the yellow stars are older and cooler. It is around 29,000 light years away.

fields.name: NGC6426
fields.description: NGC 6426 is a globular cluster located in the constellation Ophiuchus, 66,500 light years away.

fields.name: NGC6207
fields.description: NGC 6207 is a spiral galaxy located in the constellation Hercules. NGC 6207 is located at about 30 million light years from earth near the globular cluster Messier 13.

fields.name: NGC6503
fields.description: NGC6503 is a nearly edge-on spiral galaxy about 17 million light years away.

fields.name: NGC5806
fields.description: NGC5806 is a faint, barred spiral galaxy in the constellation of Virgo.

fields.name: NGC5812
fields.description: NGC5812 is an elliptical galaxy in the constellation of Libra.

fields.name: NGC5964
fields.description: NGC5964 is a barred spiral galaxy in the constellation of Serpens.

fields.name: NGC6015
fields.description: NGC6015 is a spiral galaxy in the constellation of Draco about 50 million light years away.

fields.name: NGC6118
fields.description: NGC6118 is a faint spiral galaxy in the constellation of Serpens.

fields.name: NGC6181
fields.description: NGC 6181 is a barred spiral galaxy located in the constellation Hercules, 107 million light years away.

fields.name: NGC6340
fields.description: NGC6340 is a lenticular galaxy - a disk galaxy similar to a spiral, but with no spiral arms.

fields.name: NGC6384
fields.description: NGC6384 is a face-on spiral galaxy about 60 million light years away.

fields.name: IC4592
fields.description: IC 4592 (also known as the Blue Horsehead Nebula) is a reflection nebula in the Scorpius constellation that is lit by the star Nu Scorpii.

fields.name: IC4603
fields.description: IC4603 is a Bright nebula in the Ophiuchus Constellation. This is one of the nearest star forming regions and the intricacies of the dense interstellar dust clouds in the area provide a spectacular display of light and shade; the contrasting hues making this one of the most dramatic and colourful patches of the entire night sky.

fields.name: NGC6058
fields.description: NGC6058 is a planetary nebula in the Hercules Constellation.

fields.name: NGC6517
fields.description: NGC6517 is a globular cluster about 70,000 light years away, lying on the far side of our Galaxy.

fields.name: NGC6522
fields.description: NGC6522 is a globular cluster lying at a distance of 25,400 light years, in the direction of our Galaxy's centre.

fields.name: NGC6553
fields.description: NGC6553 is a globular cluster located 18,250 light years away. It is located in the central bulge of our Galaxy, and is therefore obscured slightly by gas and dust.

fields.name: M56
fields.description: Messier 56 is a globular star cluster located in the small northern constellation Lyra. M56 lies at a distance of 32,900 light years from Earth.

fields.name: M71
fields.description: Messier 71 is a globular cluster located in the small northern constellation Sagitta, the Arrow. The cluster lies at an approximate distance of 13,000 light years from Earth.

fields.name: M75
fields.description: Messier 75 is a globular cluster in the constellation Sagittarius. M75 is at a distance of about 67,500 light years away from Earth.

fields.name: M72
fields.description: Messier 72 is a globular cluster in the Aquarius constellation discovered by French astronomer Pierre Méchain on August 29, 1780. This GC is at a distance of about 53,000 light years. The older, yellow stars and the younger blue stars are clear to see.

fields.name: NGC6946
fields.description: NGC 6946 (also tentatively known as the Fireworks Galaxy) is a spiral galax,y about 22 million light-years away, in the constellations of Cepheus and Cygnus.

fields.name: NGC6643
fields.description: NGC6643 is a spiral galaxy with a small nucleus (centre) and spiral arms.

fields.name: NGC6654
fields.description: NGC6654 is a faint galaxy in the constellation of Draco. It is classified as a barred lenticular galaxy, meaning that it has a disk shape (as do spiral galaxies) with a bar running through the centre, but it has no spiral arms.

fields.name: NGC6814
fields.description: NGC6814 is a face-on spiral galaxy, which can be viewed through the inner arm of our own galaxy, the Milky Way.

fields.name: NGC6951
fields.description: NGC6951 is a good example of a barred spiral galaxy, as the bar can be clearly seen stretching out from the centre of this galaxy. Two supernovae have gone off in this galaxy, one in 1999 and one in 2000.

fields.name: NGC6703
fields.description: NGC6703 is a lenticular galaxy in the constellation of Lyra. Lenticular galaxies have a disc-shape, similar to our Galaxy, but no spiral arms.

fields.name: IC4605
fields.description: This is a reflection nebula in the constellation of Ophiucus. Gas in the region surrounding the star 22 Scorpious is reflecting the star light, resulting in this nebula being visible.

fields.name: M17
fields.description: The Omega Nebula, also known as the Swan Nebula, Checkmark Nebula, and the Horseshoe Nebula in the constellation Sagittarius.

fields.name: IC1318
fields.description: The Sadr region, or IC 1318, is the nebula surrounding the star called Sadr. The nebula itself is more than 3000 light years away from us.

fields.name: IC1287
fields.description: IC1287 is a Bright nebula in the Scutum Constellation. This nebula appears blue after reflecting light from the nearby star.

fields.name: NGC6914
fields.description: NGC 6914 is a reflection nebula located at approximately 6,000 light-years away in the constellation of Cygnus, and was discovered by Édouard Stephan on August 29, 1881.

fields.name: NGC6572
fields.description: NGC6572 is a planetary nebula in the constellation of Ophiuchus, about 4000 light years away.

fields.name: M57
fields.description: This Planetary Nebula, also known as the 'Ring Nebula', was thought to have formed 1000 years ago when an old star blew off its surrounding material. The inner part of the nebula which appears dark is actually emitting hot, UV radiation which is invisible to our eyes. The central white dwarf star is planet sized, and was probably once a Sun-like star which blew away its outer layers. At a current tempertaure of 100,000K, the white dwarf will eventually cool down, and after a few billion years, end up as a cold Black Dwarf.

fields.name: M27
fields.description: Nicknamed `The Dumbell Nebula', this planetary nebula is an excellent example of a bipolar nebula, whose shape is caused by a hot wind slamming into gas released from the centre of a dying star.

fields.name: NGC6804
fields.description: NGC6804 is a planetary nebula. The central star in this nebula can be seen clearly with its expanding shells of gas.

fields.name: NGC6842
fields.description: NGC6842 is quite a faint planetary nebula in the constellation of Vulpecula. It was first discovered by Albert Marth on June 28, 1863.

fields.name: NGC6960
fields.description: NGC6960 is part of the enormous "Veil Nebula" - the gas left behind after the detonation of a supernova. The nebula is around 2,000 light years distant, and has a diameter of around 100 light years.

fields.name: M15
fields.description: This is a very dense globular cluster with a concentrated centre which may contain a black hole. At an estimated 12.0 billion years old, it is one of the oldest known globular cluster.

fields.name: M2
fields.description: This globular cluster contains approximately 150,000 stars. It lies around 40,000 light years away.

fields.name: Pal12
fields.description: Pal12 is a globular cluster that lies about 62,000 light years from us. It was originally thought to be a galaxy known as a "dwarf galaxy" in our Local Group of galaxies.

fields.name: NGC7318A
fields.description: NGC 7318 is a pair of interacting galaxies, about 390 million light years away, in the direction of the Pegasus constellation.

fields.name: NGC7331
fields.description: NGC7331 is a spiral galaxy an estimated 50 million light years away. X-ray observations suggest that the centre of this galaxy may contain a massive black hole.

fields.name: NGC7479
fields.description: NGC 7479 (also known as Caldwell 44) is a barred spiral galaxy about 105 million light-years away in the constellation Pegasus. This is a beautiful barred spiral galaxy, seen almost face on.

fields.name: NGC7013
fields.description: NGC 7013 is a relatively nearby spiral or lenticular galaxy estimated to be around 37 to 41.4 million light-years away from Earth in the constellation of Cygnus. It has a diameter of about 44,000 light-years.

fields.name: NGC7042
fields.description: NGC 7042 is a spiral galaxy located about 234 million light-years away in the constellation of Pegasus. It has an estimated diameter of 146,200 light-years.

fields.name: NGC7102
fields.description: NGC7102 is a distant barred spiral galaxy in the constellation of Pegasus. It has a small bright nucleus with a central bar.

fields.name: NGC7023
fields.description: NGC 7023 is actually the cluster within the nebula known as the Iris Nebula and Caldwell 4 - a bright reflection nebula in the constellation Cepheus 1,300 light years away.

fields.name: IC1396
fields.description: The Elephant's Trunk nebula is a concentration of space gas and dust within the much larger nebula of IC 1396 which is located in the constellation Cepheus about 2,400 light years away from Earth.

fields.name: Sh2-155
fields.description: Sh2-155 is a nebula visible due to the energy from young stars, embedded within, which ionises the cloud of cool gas.

fields.name: NGC7293
fields.description: NGC7293, also known as the Helix Nebula, is a large planetary nebula located in the constellation Aquarius. The Helix Nebula is relatively close, at a distance of around 450 light years.

fields.name: NGC1169
fields.description: NGC 1169 is a barred spiral galaxy in the constellation of Perseus. It has a reddish center, indicating the region is dominated by older stars. In contrast, the outer ring contains larger blue-white stars, a sign of recent star formation.

fields.name: NGC1179
fields.description: NGC1179 is a faint face-on spiral galaxy in the constellation of Eridanus.

fields.name: NGC1931
fields.description: NGC1931 is an open cluster and emission nebula approximately 7000 light years away. At 10 million years old, this is fairly young, hence why the emission nebula from which the stars formed, is still visible.

fields.name: IC434
fields.description: IC 434 is a bright emission nebula in the constellation Orion. It was discovered on February 1, 1786 by William Herschel. This nebula is part of the famous `Horsehead Nebula' in Orion.

fields.name: NGC2024
fields.description: NGC 2024, sometimes known as the "Flame Nebula", is a star-forming region located near the star Zeta Orionis in Orion's Belt.

fields.name: NGC1535
fields.description: NGC1535 is a planetary nebula located at a distance of about 6,000 light years in the constellation of Eridanus.

fields.name: NGC2403
fields.description: NGC2403 is a spiral galaxy located 11.5 million light years away.

fields.name: NGC2683
fields.description: NGC2683 is a nearly edge-on spiral galaxy at a distance of about 30 million light years.

fields.name: NGC2655
fields.description: NGC2655 is a lenticular galaxy (a disk galaxy, similar to the Milky Way, but with no spiral arm structure) about 80 million light years away.

fields.name: NGC2681
fields.description: NGC2681 is a lenticular galaxy (a disk galaxy, similar to the Milky Way, but with no spiral arm structure) about 45 million light years away in the constellation of Ursa Major. Its centre is thought to contain a black-hole with a mass of about 8 million suns.

fields.name: NGC2146
fields.description: NGC2146 is a barred spiral galaxy that has been part of an interaction with another galaxy, resulting in its peculiar shape.

fields.name: NGC2196
fields.description: NGC2196 is a rather small, face-on spiral galaxy in the constellation of Lepus.

fields.name: NGC2247
fields.description: NGC2247 is a reflection nebula located in the constellation of Monoceros. It appears as a faint, hazy circular glow surrounding a brighter star.

fields.name: NGC2245
fields.description: NGC2245 is a nebula made up of gas and dust reflecting light from a nearby star.

fields.name: IC446
fields.description: IC446 is a Bright nebula in the Monoceros Constellation. It appears to be several thousand light years behind the more famous Cone Nebula.

fields.name: IC443
fields.description: IC 443 (also known as the Jellyfish Nebula) is a supernova remnant in the constellation Gemini. It is roughly 5,000 light years from Earth. IC 443 may be the remains of a supernova that occurred 3,000 - 30,000 years ago. A neutron star, the remains of the star which exploded, was recently discovered inside this cloud of glowing gas.

fields.name: NGC2903
fields.description: NGC2903 is a barred spiral galaxy approximately 30 million light years away. It has a rather mottled appearance due to the many star-forming regions in its spiral arms which show up as bright spots along the arms.

fields.name: M82
fields.description: This is an irregular galaxy in the constellation of Ursa Major, 13 million light years away. It is one of a group of galaxies, and is thought to have recently been involved in an interaction with its close neighbour, the spiral galaxy, M81. It is this interaction which is thought to have caused the dust lanes which are prominent in this galaxy, and visible as the dark patches throughout the galaxy.

fields.name: NGC3184
fields.description: NGC3184 is a nearly face-on spiral galaxy, about 30 million light years away. It has several bright regions visible in its spiral arms, which are the sites of star formation.

fields.name: NGC3344
fields.description: NGC3344 is a barred spiral galaxy in the constellation of Leo, about 20 million light years away. Several star forming regions are visible in the spiral arms as bright spots.

fields.name: NGC3521
fields.description: NGC3521 is a barred spiral galaxy, located approximately 25 million light years away in the constellation of Leo. Regions of star formation in the arms can be seen as blue patches.

fields.name: M66
fields.description: This barred spiral galaxy has both bright regions in its spiral arms, where stars are forming, and darker lanes where dust is obscuring the light. Also visible in the image is a bright foreground star.

fields.name: NGC7213
fields.description: NGC7213 is one of the brightest of the spirals in the constellation of Grus, 70 million light years ago.

fields.name: NGC7410
fields.description: NGC7410 is a spiral galaxy seen slightly edge-on, thus appears quite elongated. It lies 76 million light years from Earth.

fields.name: IC1459
fields.description: IC 1459 is an elliptical galaxy that is about 68.8 million light-years from us in the Constellation of the Crane at the border with the Australian Fish and the Sculptor. This Elliptical galaxy has a supermassive black hole at its centre.

fields.name: IC5264
fields.description: IC 5264 is a spiral galaxy that is about 89 million light years from the Earth and is located in the constellation Ždral. The first discovery was made by Lewis Swift on June 10, 1896 .

fields.name: NGC7418
fields.description: NGC 7418 is a barred spiral galaxy and is located 63 million light years away in the Crane Constellation.

fields.name: NGC7421
fields.description: NGC7421 is a spiral galaxy with a prominent bar at its centre. It appears to sit slightly offset from the centre of its envelope. NGC7421 is at a distance of 79.6 million light years in the Grus Constellation.

fields.name: NGC7418A
fields.description: NGC7418A is a spiral galaxy with a brighter central region and fainter, diffuse spiral arms. NGC7418A lies 91 million light years away in the Grus Constellation.

fields.name: IC5148
fields.description: This beautiful planetary nebula was discovered by an amateur astronomer in 1894. It has a hole at its centre surrounding it's central star, enveloped by a ring of material. It is roughly 3449 light years away from us.

fields.name: HCG37
fields.description: HCG37 is a Galaxy cluster in the Cancer Constellation. This set of five galaxies all packed together has two dominant galaxies.

fields.name: HCG41
fields.description: HCG41 is a Galaxy cluster in the Ursa Major Constellation. This group consists of four galaxies. Interestingly all of the physical aspects of this galaxy group are different, so we think this is a chance event.

fields.name: HCG45
fields.description: HCG45 is a Galaxy cluster in the Ursa Major Constellation. This group of galaxies is a loose set of four spiral galaxies.  A large visible dust trail can be seen in galaxy.

fields.name: HCG49
fields.description: HCG49 is a Galaxy cluster in the Ursa Major Constellation. This is a small set of four galaxies that are very closely packed together.

fields.name: HCG50
fields.description: HCG50 is a Galaxy cluster in the Ursa Major Constellation. This is a small ring shaped set of five galaxies.  The group of galaxies is thought to have a large concentration of dark matter.

fields.name: HCG55
fields.description: HCG55 is a Galaxy cluster in the Draco constellation. This group is made up of five closely packed galaxies.

fields.name: HCG56
fields.description: HCG56 is a Galaxy cluster in the Ursa Major Constellation. This group is made up of five galaxies, three of which appear to be in contact and interacting.

fields.name: HCG60
fields.description: HCG60 is a Galaxy cluster in the Ursa Major Constellation. This galaxy group is a very tightly packed arrangement of galaxies within a cluster.

fields.name: HCG66
