fields.description: HCG66 is a Galaxy cluster in the Ursa Major constellation. This is a distant chain of four galaxies.

fields.name: HCG78
fields.description: HCG78 is a Galaxy cluster in the Draco Constellation. This set of four galaxies contains only two galaxies that are travelling at similar speeds.

fields.name: HCG80
fields.description: HCG80 is a Galaxy cluster in the Draco Constellation. This is a group of four spiral of galaxies.

fields.name: HCG82
fields.description: HCG82 is a Galaxy cluster in the Hercules Constellation. This group of galaxies is a relatively spread out set of four galaxies.

fields.name: HCG84
fields.description: HCG84 is a Galaxy cluster in the Ursa Minor Constellation. This group is made up of a set of four galaxies and one galaxy that is moving away at a really fast pace.

fields.name: HCG85
fields.description: HCG85 is a Galaxy cluster in Draco constellation. This is a small set of four galaxies.

fields.name: HCG92
fields.description: This is a famous group Stephan's Quintet.  It was the first compact group discovered, it is dense set of four galaxies plus a bright low speed spiral galaxy. Stephan's Quintet is a Galaxy cluster in the Pegasus Constellation.

fields.name: NGC1788
fields.description: NGC1788 is a reflection nebula located 2000 light years away in the constellation of Orion. The nebula appears blue in colour due to blue light scattering off gas and dust in the nebula.

fields.name: NGC2169
fields.description: NGC2169 is an open cluster located 3,000 light years away. It was discovered in 1784 by William Herschel.

fields.name: NGC2186
fields.description: NGC2186 is an open cluster located 5,000 light years away. It was discovered in 1786 by William Herschel.

fields.name: NGC7177
fields.description: NGC7177 is a small spiral galaxy 49.9 million light years away in the Pegasus constellation. It contains a central bulge surrounded by a bright disc.

fields.name: NGC7339
fields.description: NGC 7332 and NGC 7339 are an isolated, bound pair of galaxies about 67 million light years away. NGC 7339 is an edge on spiral that is unusually blue.

fields.name: NGC2452
fields.description: NGC 2452 is a planetary nebula located in the southern constellation of Puppis.

fields.name: NGC2525
fields.description: NGC2525 is an impressive face-on barred spiral galaxy located 68 million light years away in the Puppis constellation.

fields.name: NGC2298
fields.description: NGC2298 is a small globular cluster located 34,900 light years away. It was discovered in 1826 by James Dunlop.

fields.name: NGC2627
fields.description: NGC 2627 is an open cluster located 6,500 light years away, containing about 60 faint stars.

fields.name: NGC2658
fields.description: NGC2658 is an open cluster contains about 80 stars. It lies about 1,532 light years away.

fields.name: NGC2613
fields.description: NGC2613 is a fine example of a spiral galaxy inclined from our line of sight so that we see it nearly edge-on. It's located 65 million light years away.

fields.name: NGC2888
fields.description: NGC2888 is a small elliptical galaxy located 106 million light years away.

fields.name: M54
fields.description: Messier 54 is a globular cluster in the constellation Sagittarius. This is a highly concentrated globular cluster that is around 87,400 light years away from us.

fields.name: M18
fields.description: Messier 18 or M18 is an open cluster of stars in the constellation Sagittarius. This open cluster only has about 20 members. Its age is estimated at 32 million years and it is 4,900 light-years away.

fields.name: M8
fields.description: The Lagoon Nebula, M8, is a giant interstellar cloud in the constellation Sagittarius. The Lagoon Nebula is estimated to be between 4,000-6,000 light-years from the Earth.

fields.name: NGC121
fields.description: NGC 121 is a globular cluster located 210, 000 light years away in the Small Magellanic Cloud a nearby dwarf galaxy. It was first discovered by John Herschel on September 20, 1835.

fields.name: NGC0371
fields.description: NGC0371 is a bright open cluster situated 210,000 light years away in the Small Magellanic cloud, a small irregular galaxy orbiting our Milky Way galaxy.

fields.name: NGC2792
fields.description: NGC2792 is a fairly small Planetary Nebula lying 9,000 light years away in the constellation of Vela.

fields.name: NGC2660
fields.description: NGC2660 is an open cluster that looks very similar to a globular cluster. It lies 9,212 light years.

fields.name: IC2488
fields.description: The stars in this open cluster are quite spaced out, and are mainly blue, although there are also a few yellow stars. The cluster itself is around 3700 light years away.

fields.name: HCG2
fields.description: HCG2 is a set of three galaxies, two bright galaxies and one faint galaxy.

fields.name: HCG11
fields.description: HCG11 is a Galaxy Cluster in the Cetus Constellation. This group comprises of a spiral galaxy surrounded by three smaller galaxies.

fields.name: HCG14
fields.description: HCG14 is a Galaxy Cluster in the Cetus Constellation. This group consists of three interacting galaxies.

fields.name: HCG15
fields.description: HCG15 is a Group of Galaxies in the Cetus Constellation. This is a group of six galaxies, the brightest galaxy is interacting with another galaxy in the group.

fields.name: HCG16
fields.description: The galaxies in this group shine brightly with their glowing golden centres and wispy tails of gas, set against a background dotted with much more distant galaxies.

fields.name: HCG21
fields.description: HCG21 is a Galaxy Cluster in the Eridanus Constellation. This group is made up of a set of three spread out galaxies and a fainter pair of galaxies. The brightest galaxy has two extending spiral arms.

fields.name: HCG22
fields.description: HCG22 is a Galaxy cluster in the Eridanus Constellation. This group consists of a set of three galaxies, including a large elliptical galaxy, and two spiral galaxies.

fields.name: HCG23
fields.description: HCG23 is a Galaxy cluster in the Eridanus Constellation. This group of galaxies contains a set of four small galaxies and a small very fast moving galaxy.

fields.name: HCG25
fields.description: HCG25 is a Galaxy cluster in the Cetus Constellation. This group of galaxies is made up of 8 galaxies.

fields.name: HCG30
fields.description: HCG30 is a Galaxy cluster in the Eridanus Constellation. This is a spread out set of 4 galaxies where most of them are spiral galaxies.

fields.name: HCG88
fields.description: HCG88 is a Galaxy cluster in the Aquarius Constellation. This is a loose collection of four spiral galaxies.

fields.name: HCG89
fields.description: HCG89 is a Galaxy cluster in the Aquarius constellation. This is a faint, set of four of spiral galaxies.

fields.name: HCG90
fields.description: HCG90 is a Galaxy cluster in the Pisces Austrinus Constellation. This is a collection of four interacting galaxies.

fields.name: HCG91
fields.description: HCG91 is a Galaxy cluster in the Pisces Austrinus Constellation. This group is a collection of four galaxies and contains a set of galaxies that are interacting with each other.

fields.name: HCG7
fields.description: HCG7 is a group of galaxies in the Cetus Constellation.  This group consists of four bright spiral galaxies.

fields.name: HCG93
fields.description: HCG93 is a galaxy cluster in the Pegasus Constellation. This group consists of a set of four very similar galaxies plus a fainter galaxy that is moving away from us very quickly.

fields.name: HCG97
fields.description: HCG97 is a Galaxy cluster in the Pisces Constellation. This group is a loose group of five galaxies.

fields.name: M4
fields.description: Messier 4 is a bright globular cluster located in the southern constellation Scorpius. It lies at an approximate distance of 7,200 light years from Earth.

fields.name: M5
fields.description: Messier 5 is a bright globular cluster located in the northern constellation Serpens. The cluster lies at a distance of 24,500 light years from Earth, in the galactic halo of the Milky Way.

fields.name: M7
fields.description: Messier 7, also known as Ptolemy’s Cluster, is a bright open cluster in Scorpius constellation. The cluster lies at an approximate distance of 980 light years from Earth.

fields.name: M6
fields.description: Messier 6, also known as the Butterfly Cluster, is an open cluster of stars in the constellation of Scorpius. Its name derives from the vague resemblance of its shape to a butterfly.

fields.name: M19
fields.description: Messier 19 is a globular cluster in the constellation Ophiuchus. It was discovered by Charles Messier on June 5, 1764.

fields.name: M20
fields.description: The Trifid Nebula, also known as Messier 20 is in the Sagittarius Constellation. The Trifid Nebula is a star-forming region in the Scutum spiral arm of the Milky Way. The most massive star that has formed in this region has a mass more than 20 times the mass of the Sun. This star is surrounded by a cluster of approximately 3100 young stars.

fields.name: M21
fields.description: Messier 21 (M21) is an open cluster located in the southern constellation Sagittarius. The cluster lies at about 4,250 light years from Earth. M21 consists mainly of small, faint stars, but is also home to a few blue giants.

fields.name: M23
fields.description: Messier 23 is an open cluster in the constellation Sagittarius. Messier 23 is only 2,150 light-years away, and hence it stands out with its stars looking brighter and bigger against the backdrop of the Milky Way.

fields.name: M26
fields.description: Open Cluster M26 is an open cluster in the constellation of Scutum. M26 is at a distance of 5,000 light years from the Earth. This cluster is estimated to be 89 million years old.

fields.name: M29
fields.description: Messier 29 is an open cluster located in the constellation Cygnus, the Swan. Messier 29 is too faint to be spotted by the naked eye, but can be seen in binoculars. The cluster lies at an approximate distance of 4,000 light years from Earth.

fields.name: M35
fields.description: Messier 35 is a large open star cluster located in the northern constellation Gemini. The cluster consists of several hundred stars, of which 120 are very bright.

fields.name: M36
fields.description: Messier 36, also known as the Pinwheel Cluster, is an open cluster located in the northern constellation Auriga, the Charioteer.

fields.name: M37
fields.description: Messier 37 is the richest open cluster in the constellation Auriga. Messier 37 is the brightest, richest and largest of the three open clusters in this constellation that were catalogued by Messier. The cluster has a distance of 4,511 light years from Earth.

fields.name: M38
fields.description: Messier 38, also known as the Starfish Cluster, is an open star cluster located in the northern constellation Auriga. The cluster lies at a distance of 4,200 light years from Earth.

fields.name: M41
fields.description: Messier 41 is a bright open star cluster located in Canis Major constellation. It lies near Sirius, the brightest star in the sky. Messier 41 is around 2,300 light years from Earth.

fields.name: M42
fields.description: The Orion Nebula, also known as Messier 42, is a nebula situated in the Milky Way, being south of Orion's Belt in the constellation of Orion. It is one of the brightest nebulae, and is visible to the naked eye in the night sky.

fields.name: M43
fields.description: Messier 43, also known as De Mairan’s Nebula, is a star-forming nebula located in the constellation Orion. M43 is around 1,600 light years from Earth.

fields.name: M46
fields.description: Messier 46 is an open cluster in the constellation of Puppis. It was discovered by Charles Messier in 1771. Dreyer described it as "very bright, very rich, very large."

fields.name: M47
fields.description: Messier 47 is a bright open star cluster located in the southern constellation Puppis. The cluster lies at a distance of 1,600 light years from Earth.

fields.name: M48
fields.description: Messier 48 is an open star cluster located in Hydra, the largest constellation in the sky. The cluster lies at a distance of 1,500 light years from Earth.

fields.name: M49
fields.description: Messier 49 is an elliptical galaxy located in the southern constellation Virgo. The galaxy lies at a distance of 55.9 million light years from Earth.

fields.name: M50
fields.description: Messier 50, nicknamed the Heart-Shaped Cluster, is a large, bright open cluster located in the constellation Monoceros. The cluster is around 3,200 light years away from Earth.

fields.name: M52
fields.description: Messier 52 is a bright open cluster located in the northern constellation Cassiopeia. The cluster lies at an approximate distance of 5,000 light years from Earth.

fields.name: M55
fields.description: Messier 55, also known as the Summer Rose Star, is a globular cluster located in the constellation Sagittarius. The cluster lies at a distance of 17,600 light years from Earth.

fields.name: M58
fields.description: Messier 58 is a barred spiral galaxy located within the constellation Virgo, approximately 68 million light-years away from Earth.

fields.name: M59
fields.description: Messier 59 is an elliptical galaxy located in the southern constellation Virgo. M59 lies at an approximate distance of 60 million light years from Earth.

fields.name: M60
fields.description: Messier 60 is an elliptical galaxy approximately 55 million light-years away in the constellation Virgo. At the centre of this galaxy is a black hole that is the mass of 4.5 billion suns, and is one of the largest ever found.

fields.name: M62
fields.description: Messier 62 is a globular star cluster located in the southern constellation Ophiuchus. The cluster lies at an approximate distance of 22,200 light years from Earth.

fields.name: M65
fields.description: Messier 65 is an intermediate spiral galaxy about 35 million light-years away in the constellation Leo.

fields.name: M69
fields.description: Messier 69 is a globular star cluster located in the southern constellation Sagittarius. Messier 69 lies at a distance of 29,700 light years from Earth.

fields.name: M70
fields.description: Messier 70 is a globular cluster located inside the southern constellation Sagittarius. The cluster lies at a distance of 29,400 light years from Earth.

fields.name: M80
fields.description: Messier 80 is a globular cluster in the constellation Scorpius. It was discovered by Charles Messier in 1781.

fields.name: M81
fields.description: Messier 81 (also known as Bode's Galaxy) is a spiral galaxy about 12 million light-years away in the constellation Ursa Major.

fields.name: M83
fields.description: Messier 83 is a barred spiral galaxy approximately 15 million light-years away in the constellation Hydra.

fields.name: M88
fields.description: M88 (also known as NGC 4501) is a spiral galaxy about 50 to 60 million light years away in the Virgo cluster of galaxies.

fields.name: M93
fields.description: M93 (also known as NGC 2447) is an open cluster located 3,600 light years away in the constellation Puppis. The cluster is about 100 million years old.

fields.name: M94
fields.description: Messier 94 (also known as NGC 4736) is a spiral galaxy located about 16 million light years away in the constellation Canes Venatici. The galaxy contains two ring structures.

fields.name: M98
fields.description: Messier 98 is a spiral galaxy located about 44 million light years away in the constellation Coma Berenices. The galaxy is a member of the Virgo cluster of galaxies.

fields.name: M99
fields.description: Messier 99 is a spiral galaxy located 50 million light years away in the constellation Coma Berenices. It was one of the first spiral galaxies to be identified.

fields.name: M100
fields.description: Messier 100 is a spiral galaxy located within the southern part of constellation Coma Berenices. It is one of the brightest and largest galaxies in the Virgo Cluster, located approximately 55 million light-years away from Earth.The galaxy was one of the first spiral galaxies to be discovered.

fields.name: M106
fields.description: Messier 106 is a spiral galaxy in the constellation Canes Venatici. M106 is about 22 to 25 million light-years away from Earth. A supernova was observed in this galaxy in May 2014

fields.name: M108
fields.description: Messier 108 is a barred spiral galaxy in the constellation Ursa Major. From the perspective of the Earth, this galaxy is seen almost edge-on.

fields.name: M110
fields.description: Messier 110 is a small elliptical galaxy that is a satellite of the Andromeda Galaxy. M110 contains some dust and hints of recent star formation, which is unusual for small elliptical galaxies.

fields.name: M11
fields.description: Messier 11 is also know as the Wild Duck Cluster, it is an open cluster in the constellation Scutum. The Wild Duck Cluster is one of the richest and most compact of the known open clusters, containing about 2900 stars. Its estimated to be around 250 million years old.

fields.name: M12
fields.description: Messier 12 is a globular cluster in the constellation of Ophiuchus. It was discovered by the French astronomer Charles Messier  who described it as a "nebula without stars".

fields.name: NGC6872
fields.description: NGC6872, known as the Condor galaxy, is a barred spiral galaxy in the constellation Pavo. This galaxy is approximately 5 billion years old, and is interacting with the much smaller lenticular galaxy IC4970.

fields.name: NGC2207
fields.description: NGC2207 and IC2163 are a pair of colliding spiral galaxies in the constellation Canis Major. They were both discovered by John Herschel in 1835, and are located about 80 million light years away.
